The stolen passports used by two men to board the Beijing-bound Malaysia Airlines (MAS) MH370, which went missing last Saturday, were not on the Interpol's suspect list (SL).Home Minister Datuk Seri Dr Ahmad Zahid Hamidi said that is how the two men were able to pass through the check at the immigration counter."If Interpol had marked 'SL' for the missing passports, all the Immigration counters nationwide would be on the alert."(Therefore) I am confident with the capability of the immigration officers who were at the checkpoint counter before the incident," he said in Kajang today.Earlier today, Inspector-General of Police Tan Sri Khalid Abu Bakar said the police had identified an Iranian, Pouri Nourmohammadi, 19, as one of the passengers who boarded the aircraft with the stolen passports.The Iranian had used a passport belonging to an Austrian, Christian Kozel, who had reported it missing in Thailand.As for the other passport, which belonged to Italian Luigi Maraldi, Interpol confirmed that it was used by Delavar Seyed Mohammad Redza, 30, also an Iranian.Interpol secretary-general Ronald K. Noble, at a press conference in Lyon, France, that the two men travelled to Malaysia on their Iranian passports, then apparently switched to the stolen Austrian and Italian documents.MAS Flight MH370, carrying 227 passengers, including two infants, and 12 crew, went missing en route from Kuala Lumpur to Beijing about an hour after taking off from the KL International Airport at 12.41am Saturday.On the negative reports by the Chinese media on the handling of the missing aircraft by the Malaysian government, the minister said they should exercise patience as Malaysia was doing its best. â€“ Bernama, March 11, 2014.